text.tspan: Prevalence of modern contraception methods vs. women's average years
Shown is the share of women who are practicing, or whose sexual partners are practicing, at least one modern method of
contraception. It is usually measured for women ages 15-49 who are married or in union.
Mean years of schooling of women in the reproductive age bracket (15 to 49).
Note: Modern methods of contraception include female and male sterilization, oral hormonal pills, the
intra-uterine device (IUD), the male condom, injectables, the implant (including Norplant), vaginal barrier
methods, the female condom and emergency contraception.
Data source: Data compiled from multiple sources by World Bank, Our World In Data (2017)
